Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[telegram] <Cabey> I suspect most exchanges keep this information close to their chest but tens of thousands of wallets seems like a lot, do you know of any good behind the scenes type video or article on running an exchange (re @Regnar: It isn't necessarily "maintenance". All the exchanges are informed of hard updates to the chain weeks in advance to ensure they are all ready to update their wallets when it comes time. This isn't Komodo saying disable your wallets weeks in advance for "reasons" or anything, in fact some exchanges still have wallets open and will likely keep them open until a day or two prior. 
Exchanges manage their own risk in this way. Exchanges like Binance play it safe and will disable deposits and withdrawals likely so they can either prepare to update the tens of thousands of KMD wallets they have, or so they can consolidate funds in cold storage, update all their hot wallets, and so on.)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[telegram] <Regnar> I think it's important to remember that right now Atomicdex is a mobile app. Due to space, resource, and hardware restrictions it likely wont have the same level of features as Binance Mobile. I could be wrong here, Atomicdex may end up like this. However Binance uses APIs to their own servers which are very light, that is the benefit of being centralized, but with the obvious drawbacks (sim swap attacks, hacks, disabled wallets, regulation etc) (re @Craig: Thanks for all the in depth responses regnar. You're a passionate guy. 
Let me try to phrase a question that's important to me. 
Take IDEX.
You visit the website and there's a funny thing you need to do, "unlocking your wallet". A few other funny things later when you want to "withdraw"
This throws off some people. But people know it's a DEX or something a little weird. So most people push on past the weirdness.
Honestly it's probably because IDEX has interesting coins that aren't listed anywhere else, not because the average user really cares about holding their keys.
 But no worries, they push on.
One big reason is they push on is because there's a list of like 100 tokens, visible on the front page, that gives their daily volume and % change in price. Also there are charts. Basically it looks like an underdesigned version of binance or another CEX.
The user then goes about his business trading with just a few quirks. Also things are slow, the website kinda lags, but it's ok because it's a DEX and a lot of coins are only possible to find there.
So the vision for atomicDEX, is it similar to that? Where a user will have to accept a few minor annoying tradeoffs in order to trade in a way roughly like a centralized exchange? 
Or is using atomicDEX going to be a radically different experience than a centralized exchange?
Another way to put it:
What tradeoffs will atomic dex accept, and what bonuses will it have besides less counterparty risk, no kycaml, your keys your coins?)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[telegram] <Regnar> But AtomicDEX isn't limited to JUST mobile, or just websites, etc. It is an API layer that shares all liquidity. There are already desktop apps that are sharing liquidity and using the Atomicapi to trade desktop with mobile. 
AtomicDEX being a mobile app, I don't expect to take on the role if a full fledged trading DEX app, it might be this in the future with charts and order types etc. But I personally think it would be better positioned against instant swap services like changelly and shapeshift, like it was suggested here to simple have a "best price/instant swap" setting. I think mobile apps should keep functionality as basic and simple as possible, let websites have tons of features. but I don't make these decisions. (re @Craig: Framing it as an OTC market helps thanks.
Here i am saying I hate trading and then complaining there aren't enough features. 
It's just, there are other DEXs out there that have, or plan to have, a lot more that OTC style markets. Im not sure I ever expected leverage or derivatives and so on with atomicDEX. 
We will see how it goes I guess)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[telegram] <Regnar> It could be a trading DEX app, or it can be a wallet with instant swap functions. I think swaps would be better for a mobile app, and desktop and website apps would be better suited for the full fledged trading experience (drawing on charts, zooming out, multiple order types, trollbox, massive orderbook views, all coin prices and changes etc) just like we see with most DEXs and CEXs. 
Again take this with a grain of salt, I'm just a community volunteer, not a decision maker for Komodo
